{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526212"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:21:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:21:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14127"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583944"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:32:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:32:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14127"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14127","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14127"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.51,0.11,0.06,0.26,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6807"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55414"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6807","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6807"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14127"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40950"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"687"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1098"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"2089"},{"type":"tags","id":"2254"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2972"},{"type":"tags","id":"3049"},{"type":"tags","id":"3519"},{"type":"tags","id":"4620"},{"type":"tags","id":"4624"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15300"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15900"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32495"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32639"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55414"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a four-hour history of nausea, vomiting, and tinnitus. She admits to ingesting an unknown quantity of aspirin tablets approximately six hours ago in a suicide attempt. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears alert but anxious. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Arterial blood gas reveals:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH: 7.45 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpCO2: 20 mmHg (35-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCO3-: 15 mmol/L (22-28)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpO2: 100 mmHg (75-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best explains the arterial blood gas findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mixed respiratory alkalosis and metabolic acidosis","Uncompensated respiratory alkalosis","Compensated respiratory acidosis","Compensated metabolic acidosis","Uncompensated metabolic alkalosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s arterial blood gas analysis shows a normal pH, low pCO2, and low HCO3-. These findings are consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003Emixed respiratory alkalosis and metabolic acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E, which is characteristic of aspirin overdose. Aspirin stimulates the respiratory centre in the brain, leading to hyperventilation and respiratory alkalosis. Additionally, it causes metabolic acidosis through the accumulation of organic acids and interference with cellular metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompensated metabolic acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E would present with a low pH and low HCO3-, with a compensatory decrease in pCO2. However, the degree of pCO2 drop in this case is much greater than would be expected from a purely compensatory change, indicating the presence of a mixed acid-base disorder. There are several formulae which exist to help distinguish this, including Winter\u0027s formula and the calculation of a delta ratio. A further clue that the pathology is not purely metabolic despite the low HCO3- is that the pH is almost approaching an alkalaemia. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUncompensated respiratory alkalosis\u003C/strong\u003E would present with a high pH and low pCO2, without a significant change in HCO3-. The presence of a low HCO3- indicates a metabolic component. This may be as a compensatory mechanism, or in this case due to the direct physiological effects of aspirin toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompensated respiratory acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E would present with a low pH and high pCO2, with a compensatory increase in HCO3-.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUncompensated metabolic alkalosis\u003C/strong\u003E would present with a high pH and high HCO3-, without a significant change in pCO2. Neither of these are consistent with the findings in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aspirin overdose typically presents with a mixed respiratory alkalosis and metabolic acidosis on arterial blood gas analysis."],"references":["Palmer BF, Clegg DJ. Salicylate Toxicity. Ingelfinger JR, editor. New England Journal of Medicine. 2020 Jun 25;382(26):2544\u201355. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32579814/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40950"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14127"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40950"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-15T14:55:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-15T14:56:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6807"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55414"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships